# Torus Symmetry Actions: Reflection, Translation, and D4

Defines symmetry transformations on the torus test function space
`TorusTestFunction L = C‚ąě(S¬Ļ_L) ‚äóŐā C‚ąě(S¬Ļ_L)` and their lifts to
configuration space.

## Main definitions

### Circle-level
- `circleReflection` ‚ÄĒ `f ‚Ü¶ f(-¬∑)` on `SmoothMap_Circle L ‚ĄĚ`
- `circleTranslation v` ‚ÄĒ `f ‚Ü¶ f(¬∑ - v)` on `SmoothMap_Circle L ‚ĄĚ`

### Tensor product lifting (axioms)
- `nuclearTensorProduct_mapCLM` ‚ÄĒ `T‚āĀ ‚äó T‚āā` on `NuclearTensorProduct`
- `nuclearTensorProduct_swapCLM` ‚ÄĒ swap factors

### Torus-level (from axioms)
- `torusTimeReflection` ‚ÄĒ `őė ‚äó id` (time reflection)
- `torusTranslation` ‚ÄĒ `T_{v‚āĀ} ‚äó T_{v‚āā}` (translation)
- `torusSwap` ‚ÄĒ swap coordinates (part of D4)

### Configuration-level
- `torusConfigReflection` ‚ÄĒ precomposition with `torusTimeReflection`
- `torusConfigTranslation` ‚ÄĒ precomposition with `torusTranslation`

## Mathematical background

The torus T¬≤_L = (‚ĄĚ/L‚Ą§)¬≤ has:
- Translation symmetry (‚ĄĚ/L‚Ą§)¬≤ acting by shift
- D4 point group (generated by coordinate swap and reflections)
- Time reflection (t, x) ‚Ü¶ (-t, x) for OS axiom OS3

CLMs on nuclear Fr√©chet spaces lift to completed tensor products
(Tr√®ves, Ch. 50). The coefficient-level action preserves rapid decay
because CLMs on DyninMityaginSpace have polynomial growth on the basis.

## References

